# 🔐 Linux File & Directory Permissions

Permissions determine **who can read, write, or execute files and directories**.

## 📌 Permission Types
| Permission | Symbol | Value | Meaning                        |
| ---------- | ------ | ----- | ------------------------------ |
| Read       | r      | 4     | View file contents             |
| Write      | w      | 2     | Modify file contents           |
| Execute    | x      | 1     | Run a file as a program/script |

---------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

## 📌 Permission Categories

Linux permissions are assigned to:

| Category | Symbol | Meaning                   |
| -------- | ------ | ------------------------- |
| User     | u      | Owner of the file         |
| Group    | g      | Users in the file's group |
| Others   | o      | Everyone else             |
| All      | a      | User + Group + Others     |

---------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

## 📌 Viewing Permissions

Use:
```command
ls -l
```

Example:
```command
-rwxr-xr-- 1 kali kali 1024 May 30 script.sh
```
### Meaning

```text
Owner  = Read, Write, Execute
Group  = Read, Execute
Others = Read Only
```

----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

# 📂 File Types

| Symbol | Type             |
| ------ | ---------------- |
| -      | Regular File     |
| d      | Directory        |
| l      | Symbolic Link    |
| c      | Character Device |
| b      | Block Device     |

Example:

```command
drwxr-xr-x
```
The `d` indicates a directory.

---------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

# 🔧 Changing Permissions with chmod

## Symbolic Method

### Add Execute Permission
```command
chmod +x script.sh
```

### Remove Write Permission
```command
chmod -w file.txt
```

### Give Owner Full Permission
```command
chmod u=rwx file.txt
```

### Give Group Read Permission
```command
chmod g+r file.txt
```
---------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

## Numeric (Octal) Method

### Permission Values

```text
Read    = 4
Write   = 2
Execute = 1
```

### Examples
#### 777
```command
chmod 777 file.sh
```

Calculation:
```text
7 = 4+2+1 = rwx
7 = 4+2+1 = rwx
7 = 4+2+1 = rwx
```

Result:
```text
rwxrwxrwx
```
** Dangerous in production.
---------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

#### 755

```command
chmod 755 script.sh
```
Result:

```text
Owner  = rwx
Group  = r-x
Others = r-x
```

Common for scripts and web files.

---------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

#### 644
```command
chmod 644 file.txt
```
Result:
```text
Owner  = rw-
Group  = r--
Others = r--
```

Most common for text files.
---------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
#### 600

```command
chmod 600 secret.txt
```
Result:
```text
Owner  = rw-
Group  = ---
Others = ---
```

Suitable for passwords and SSH keys.
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

# 👤 Changing Ownership

### Change Owner
```command
sudo chown kali file.txt
```

### Change Owner and Group
```command
sudo chown kali:developers file.txt
```

### Recursive Ownership Change
```command
sudo chown -R kali:kali project/
```

---------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

# 📂 Directory Permissions

Permissions behave differently on directories.

| Permission | Meaning                  |
| ---------- | ------------------------ |
| r          | List directory contents  |
| w          | Create/Delete files      |
| x          | Enter (access) directory |

Example:
```command
chmod 755 myfolder
```

Meaning:
```text
Owner  = Full Access
Group  = Read + Enter
Others = Read + Enter
```

---

# 🚀 Recursive Permission Changes

Apply permissions to all files and folders inside:
```command
chmod -R 755 project/
```

Recursive ownership:
```command
chown -R kali:kali project/
```

---------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

# 🔥 Special Permissions

## SUID (Set User ID)

```command
chmod u+s file
```

Display:
```text
-rwsr-xr-x
```

Allows a program to run with the owner's privileges.

Example:
```command
/usr/bin/passwd
```

---------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

## SGID (Set Group ID)
```command
chmod g+s directory
```

Display:
```text
drwxr-sr-x
```
Files created inside inherit the directory's group.
----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

## Sticky Bit
```command
chmod +t directory
```

Display:
```text
drwxrwxrwt
```

Used in:
```command
/tmp
```

Users can delete only their own files.

---------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

# 🛡️ Kali Linux Security Best Practices

✅ Use `755` for directories.
✅ Use `644` for normal files.
✅ Use `600` for sensitive files (SSH keys, passwords).
✅ Avoid `777` unless absolutely necessary.

✅ Regularly audit permissions:
```command
find /home -perm 777
```

Check file ownership:
```command
ls -la
```

Check current user:
```command
whoami
```
---------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
### Quick Cheat Sheet

```command
ls -l                # View permissions
chmod 755 file       # Set permissions
chmod +x script.sh   # Make executable
chown user file      # Change owner
chgrp group file     # Change group
chmod -R 755 dir     # Recursive permissions
chown -R user:group dir

