# Networking Commands in Kali Linux

| Command        | Purpose                                           | Syntax                  | Description                                                                                                                           |
| -------------- | ------------------------------------------------- | ----------------------- | ------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------- |
| **ifconfig**   | Display and configure network interfaces          | `ifconfig`              | Shows IP address, MAC address, and status of network interfaces. Used to enable or disable interfaces and view network configuration. |
| **ping**       | Test connectivity between hosts                   | `ping google.com`       | Sends ICMP Echo Request packets to verify network connectivity and measure response time (latency).                                   |
| **netstat**    | Display network connections and listening ports   | `netstat -tuln`         | Shows active TCP/UDP connections, listening ports, routing tables, and network statistics.                                            |
| **traceroute** | Trace the route packets take to a destination     | `traceroute google.com` | Displays each hop a packet passes through to reach the destination, helping identify network delays or routing issues.                |
| **ip**         | Manage network interfaces and routing             | `ip addr show`          | Modern replacement for `ifconfig`. Used to display and configure IP addresses, interfaces, and routing information.                   |
| **nslookup**   | Query DNS servers                                 | `nslookup google.com`   | Retrieves DNS records and verifies domain name resolution. Useful for DNS troubleshooting.                                            |
| **dig**        | Perform advanced DNS lookups                      | `dig google.com`        | Provides detailed information about DNS records and DNS server responses.                                                             |
| **arp**        | Display and manage ARP cache                      | `arp -a`                | Shows mappings between IP addresses and MAC addresses stored in the ARP table.                                                        |
| **ss**         | Display socket and network connection information | `ss -tuln`              | Modern replacement for `netstat`. Shows active connections, listening ports, and socket statistics.                                   |
| **route**      | Display and modify routing table                  | `route -n`              | Displays network routing information and default gateway settings.                                                                    |

---------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

